Meet.\nPresident O'Connell of the West\nChester and Wilmington Electric\nRailway Company has called a meet\ning of the directors of the company\nhere on Saturday morning. There will\nbe a general discussion of the com\npany's affairs at the meeting.\nA good thing to know\u2014\nthat Grape-Nuts can be di\ngested by, and quickly give\nstrength to the man or\nwoman who cannot digest\nother food.\nThe amount of promptly\navailable nourishment a food\ncontains, is the measure of\nIts value.\nGrape-Nuts is practically\nall food and is transformed\ninto tissue-building, energy\nmaking material in about\none hour aftar being eaten\u2014\nanother good thing to know.\nThere's a Reason for\nGrape-Nuts.\nMARRIED LIFE\nSUITS CLEAVER\nMan Who Married a Married\nWoman Will Marry\nAgain\nJames M. Cleaver, the Mt. Pleasant\nfarmer who got a divorce from his wife\nseveral weeks ago because the woman al\nready had a husband, will embark on \u00ab.he\nmatrimonial sea a third time, he having\nlatlon. Several years after Mr*. Cleaver)\nNo. 1 died, the farmer advertised for a\nwife and married Julia A. Tucker the\nnext day. It subsequently developed that\nJulia had a No. I husband In Indianapolis\nand as aoon as the wronged Mr. Cleaver\nmade the fact known to Superior Court he\nwas granted a decree of separation. That\nwas one month ago. And now he will\nmarry for the third time.\nobtained a license here yesterday to marry\na Smyrna woman. Just whan the liapoy\n\u00abvent will take place could not be learned.\nCleaver la a widower. He ia advanced In\nyears and has always loved the family re\nCROZIER BACK\nOF INVESTIGATION\n\nNEW YORK, March 26\u2014Alfred O\nOrozler. acting for the World, has pre\nsented a resolution to the Legislature call\ning for a probe by legislative committee\nof the entire question of slock speculation,\nMr. Crozier charged \"crooked\" transac\ntions on change and was replied to by\nJohn G. Mllburn, representing the New\nYork Stock Exchange, who said the Ex\nchange would welcome an Inquiry.\nGovernor Hughes Is believed to favor\nthe plan and the matter Is therefore In th*\nhands of the Judiciary Committee, which\nwill be urged to report It as a committee\nmeasure In place of the Wagner, the\nCuvillier and other bills which propose\nreforms In the methods of Wall street\nstock transactions.\nShipping Many Artichoksa\nCHESWOLD, March 26.\u2014George L\nBunker, is perhaps the only farmer\nin this section who ia growing a crop\nof artichokes,\nsix baskets of them and they have re\nmained as they grew all winter in the\nground. This spring-like weather they\nare being ploughed out of the ground\nand shipped la half barrel bankets.\nHe planted last year\nBISHOP ON THE\nRACE QUESTION\nRt. Rev. Daniel A. Goodsell\nSees Good Coming From\nEducation and Religion\nBishop Daniel A. Goodsell, who went\nfrom the Wilmington Conference to pre\nside over the Washington Conference of\nthe African M. E. Church in Baltimore, is\noptimistic in his outlook for the negro's\nfuture.\nBishop Goodsell's present home Is In\nBoston, but he has lived in Tennessee,\nTexas and California, and he has il.e\nhioad, national spirit of a man who knows\nthe different sections of his country thor\noughly.\n'There are no less than 1,000.000 negroes\nin the United States who claim member,\nship In the various branches of Methodist\nl&lih,\" he saya. \"In the Methodist Epis\ncopal Church our colored communicants\naggregate 300,000. Among the clergy are\nmen of the most profound piety, exten\nsive learning and manners that would be\ncome a gentleman of any race. Even peo\nple who have Intense racial prejudice\nwould have to admit, on seeing and hear\ning Dr. Bowen, who I\u00ab et th\" heed of\n'he Colored Theological Seminary at At\nlanta, Uk\u201e that\nmirable man, so Intelligent and so pol\nished as to make him persona grata in\nattj company.\n\"1 spent some years In Chattanooga and\nFort Worth, and I tell you that there le\nevery reason to hope In the future of the\nnegro. A people that emerged from cen\nturtes of slavery with nothing and that\nhas managed to accumulate \u00bb200,000,000\n\u2022luce the close of our Civil War must have\nmerit The negro is roundly abused for\nhis bad qualities and rarely gets com\nmended for his good points. For the sins\nof a few the whole race Is put under the\nban.\nEducation and Religion.\na..\n\"Education and religion are the twin\nagencies that are uplifting the American\nnegro and he is making gratifying prog\nress. Naturally, the negro Is of a religious\ntemperament, but owing to Ignorance ho\nhas not always been able to see the abso\nlute connection bet ween religion and mor\nality. This is something akin to the piety\nof the Italian brigands, who pray earn\nestly that their plana of robbery may\nprove successful.\n\"Booker Washington is on the right\ntrack with his scheme of Industrial train\ning for the black folk, but he takes credit\nnot due him for originating the policy.\nThe Methodlat Episcopal Church taught\nIt and carried It out with the greatest\nsuccess before Washington was beard of,\nand our students' exhibit at the Philadel\nphia Centennial was one of the features\nof the exposition.\"\nAlumnae Officers.\nThe High School Alumnae has elect\ned the following officers:\nMiss Edith Francis;\nMiss Elizabeth McDaniel; recording se\ncretary, Miss Nan Harkins; correspond\ning secretary, JMlsa Gertrude Meaney.\nSome time In April the association will\npresent the farce, \"A /Scrap of Paper.\"\nIt will probably be given in the New\nCentury Club,\nPrealden',\nvice-president.\nExcessive Drinking\nOrrine Destroy\u00ab the Craving for Drink\nBold Under Positive Guarantee.\nExcessive or continued use of alco\nholic beverages always result In a dis\neased condition of the nervous system.\nThe drinking man is often heard to\nsay, 'T can stop of my own free will\nand when I wish,\" but the poor fellow\nis now devoid of the power lo act at\nthe proper time and In the right way,\u2014\nit's too late, the craving has secured a\nfirm hold and because of the diseased\nnervous system be has not the ability\nfor sustained effort The result we all\nknow.\nDrunkenness is no longer considered\na crime: eminent scientists and physi\ncians have agreed that It Is a disease\nand must be treated as such.\nThe home treatment that has been\nused for a number of years, and Is\nhighly successful, is Orrine. It Is sold\nunder a positive guarantee that if It\ndoes not effect a cure your money will\nbe refunded.\nOrrine is in two forme. When de\nsiring to give secretly, purchase Or\nrine No. 1, and if the patient will vol\nuntarily take the treatment, Orrine No\n2 should be given. The guarantee Is\nthe same In either caoc Orrine costs\nbut \u00bb1.00 per box. Meljed In plain\nsealed wrapper on receipt of price.\nWrite for free treatise on \"Drunken\nness\" mailed In sealed envelope by\nThe Orrine Co,, Washington, I) C., and\nin this city by N B Danfurth A Com\npany, Second and Market streets.\nBETTER TIMERS\nARE ORGANIZED\ni\nAssociation Formed in New\nYork to Hurry the Return\nof Prosperity\nBy United Press Leased Special Wire.\nNEW YORK, March 26.\u2014Business\nmen, financiers and the public gener\nally take notice! Prosperity la soon ti\nreturn. Just as\nPresident\nKlr.ley became the \"Advance Agent of\nProsperity\" In 1896, the Better Tiroes\nAssociation, Incorporated at Albany\nlast week, and established In offices of\nMo\nIts own here to-day. Is prepared to\naume the tas|c of restoring business to\nUs highest levels.\nBefore this desirable end Is attained\nthere are heaps of trouble In store for\na few individuals, however. President\nRoosevelt, for one, may be driven to\nthe necessity of coining a few new\npletlves of a \"shorter and uglier\" va\nriety; Secretary Taft will probabiy\nhave to worry off a few pounds of\nflesh; William J. Bryan will suffer\nother disappointment, and Captain\nHarry S. New, chairman of the Repub\nlican National Commfttee, will be the\nbusiest man In the country attending\nto the mall forced upon him through\nthe good offices of the Better Timers.\nProsperity and Politics\nProsperity and politics go hand in\nhand, according to the backers of the\nnew association\u2014that's why there 1\u00bb\ntrouble ahead for the notables. The\nBett^ Timers have a platform all their\nown, with the adoption of whloh they\ndeclare prosperity Is bound to come.\nTo-day bales of literature, prepared\nby the Better Timers, Including post\ncard copies of the platform, arc being\nshipped throughout the country. Event\nt\nex\nan\nually this postal flood is to be directed\ntoward Chairman New If the plans of\nthe Better Timers do not miscarry.\nA few of the planks of this platform\nexplain the purpose of the new organi\nzation. Here they are;\n\"We stand pat on the Constitution,\nand do not want It amended by execu\ntive act, notwithstanding.\n\"We respect courts and resent execu\ntive Interference therewith, also not\nwithstanding.\n\"We believe the country Is all right\n\u2014quickly convalescing from condl\ntlons caused by overfeeding and fright\nInduced by the chief surgeon's threat to\nremove the patients liver. I\n\"Wa love a square deal, but not\neverything: so labeled. We believed\n_\npunishments should only follow proof\n__ _v u _\nof guilt, whether to colored or white,\n-7\u00ab\nTI\u00eelZ' individuals, still not\nwithstanding.\nSMALL CHEST\nWON HIM BRIDE\nDERBY, Conn.,\nla thanking his lucky stars that hts chest\ndoes not measure an Inch more. Aid', a\ncivil engineer of Bridgeport. Just of age.\nwas engoged to marry Miss Anna Goss\nman, a pretty girl of eighteen.\nComing pf age and not being natural\nized. It wa* necessary for Aldl to serve\nthree years In the Italian army before he\ncould InRSrlt considerable property at\nCaiazzo, Caeerta, Italy. He begged Miss\nAnna to marry him; then he would go to\nItaly, obey the military law and return\nto her. Naturally she refused, saying:\n\"Men are too fickle.\"\nAldl. deeply In love, was In despair,\nwhen a friend suggested to him that be\ncause of his diminutive bulj\u00a3 he is prob\nably under the standard for Italian so'\ndierg. Aldl hurried to the Italian Consul\nat New Haven and found that his chest\nmeasurement,!\u00ab one inch less than Italy\ndemands In her warriors, the Consul told\nhim he canot serve unless he grows larger.\nAldl and Miss Anna were married yes\nterday.\nHAD 65 SHIRTS,\nWANTS DIVORCE\nNEW YORK, March 26.\u2014Joshua Lowe,.\n'y V Ju d .tlce le H 0 n\u00fc kl n k \"W\nD^rJXT\ncl. Lowe, alimony at th\u00ab rat. of .16 a\nweek pending the trial oTa suit \u00abhe has\ninstituted, naming a. co-respondent\nyoung woman known on th. a,age as\nCharlotte Parry, whose real name Is Char\nlotte H. Smith.\nMra. Lowe allege, that she found her\nhusband and Miss Smith In on apart\nment In West Forty-fourth street. She\nasserts further that her husband was pos\nsessed of 12 pairs of shoes, 65 shirts and\nten suits of c'othes, and that he spent\nlarge sums of money in \"flowers and other\ngifts,\" on the woman named as co-re\nspondent.\nLowe denies all his wife's allegations,\nsave the one as to his large stock of\nshirt\u00ab. These garments, he\ngiven to him by friends. He alleges that\nthe trouble between himself and wife\ncaused by her ungovernable temper.\neay*. w\u00ab.*re\nwas\nMAKE CRATES TO\nCARRY PEACHES\nSpecial to THE EVENING JOURNAL.\nDOVER, March 26\u2014A manufactur\ning establishment has been started at\nBndgevTlle to meet and overcome the\ndemand which will certainly follow the\nPennsylvania Railroad Company's re\nfusal to hereafter shelve care for th\u00e8\ncarriage of peaches, pears and toma\ntoes.\nThe Brldgeville concern proposes to\nmake a crate which will hold two peach\nbaskets, upright. The baskets will be\nset In the crates and then a top will\nbe nailed on.\nThis will prevent the\ndumping of the fruit and save wear\nand tear on baskets. The railroad\ncompany has agreed, or will agree at\na conference here next Friday, it 1*\nsaid, to return the packages, crate,\nbaskets and all. for one cent for each\nbasket and two cents for the crate, so\nthat a farmer may use the same pack\nage several times during the tomato\nseason, get them back and use again\nfor peaches, get them again for pears.\nTit# fruit will be delivered at the\nelation a* heretofore. In peach baskets,\nand at some cent art point at the station\nthe additional packing will be done.\nThU la sold to be tho only way out\nof the prment predicament, other than\nto adopt the Georgia carrier.\nRead 11U, UViuMMU JOL'IUNAL.\nEnergy is well-nourished muscles\nplus well-nourished nerves.\n\nUneeda\na\nare the greatest energy-makers\nof all the wheat foods.\nIn dust tight,\nmoisture proof packages.\nNever sold in bulk.\n3*\nV\nNATIONAL BISCUIT COMPANY\ngpeclal to THE EVENING JOURNAL,\nDOVER, Del., March 26\u2014The ques\ntlon of whether t hl8 cou ty 8haII 8pend\nanother \u00bb30.000 to build a road to the\nBummer resort Woodland Beach> for\n._-,\nthe benefit of the pleasure-seekers who\n_.. M lo\ndesire to travel to the resort by land\n\nand the few taxables who live on\nBn Hook l8land and about\n200 a year lnt0 the county ff\u00efasury.\nhas been rolled on the shoulders of\nCounty Commissiner John P. Hudson\nMr. Hudson has been authorized by\nUie court to ascertain the probable\ncost from dredging or suction com\npares or road constructors of building\na permanent road and driveway coni\nnecting the Island with the main land,\nand to report his findings and his\nrecommendations to the court.\nThe commissioners are against this\nextraordinary expenditure and yet\nthere Is a talk on the part of the little\nhand of residents of that resort of is\nsuing a writ of mandamus upon each\nand all the members of the court com\npelling them to repair this road, which\nthe^county had already committed It\nself in favor of by bull ling at a heavy\nexpense before the tidal wave washed\naway the road and the money in a\nsingle night. Should the commissioners\nbe so ordered by such a writ, it Is said,\nthey will go Into court and press for\nan order to have this road vacated.\nWANT A ROAD TO\nWOODLAND BEACH\nResidents on the Island\nThreaten Mandamus Pro\nceedings in Kent\nVASSAR GIRLS\nPROPERLYSHOCKED\nNEW YORK, March 26\u2014A number\nof Vassar College girls visited the\nCourt of Special Sessions yesterday.\n\"We have come to study sociology,\"\nsaid their leader to the policeman at\nthe gate.\nAssistant District Attorney Keogh\nand Tinker were prosecuting a woman\n.,_. __\nPresiding Justice\nth\nT he the ral\nan( watched the woman take a roll of\ngreenbacks,.from J be ea,h her 8k\n^hocklng'r \u00abled the young atudents\nTken th ey boWed t0 th6 C0Urt a d left\nthe court room\nC aKatn 8a,d lhe b,UCCOat at\nU 1 ate\nNot y. nlc88 J\u2122 C I ha Be y0Ur Pr\n6 ramm said their leader,\nt Lippincott's Millinery Opening.\n*The formal spring showing of mil\nlinery at Lippincott Company's will\nbe held next week. The milliner ex\nperts In charge of this department are\nnow busily engaged with the various\ncreations which will be spread out for\nthe approval of women stoppers next\nWednesday and Thursday.\nThe measures and weights which\nwere In vogue in the reign of Kang Hi,\nearly in the present dynasty, are\nagain to be put in force in China, with\nslight modifications.\n4\nI\n4\nDo You Enjoy Clever Millinery\nN\n.Sn m\nm\nThen come to our store on opening days\nThursday and Friday,\nMarch 26th and 27th\nand we will let you in on some of the secrets of the trade\nMrs. Alice W. Hayes\n620 KING STREET\n\np.\n1\nStore Open Evenings\nRAILROADS TO\nATTACK RATE LAWS\nBy United Press Leased Special Wire.\nCHICAGO, March 26 -As a result of\nthe recent decision of the United States\nCourt overturning th* Minnesota State\nlaw, a conference of the presidents of\nthe railroads converging In Chicago is\nto he held soon for the purpose of at\ntacking at the same time all the rate\nlaws which have excessive penalties\nattached. It is contended by the rail\nroad officials that the same defects\nwhich marked the Minnesota and\nNorth Carolina laws are salient fea\ntures of most of the other State rate\nlaws.\nRate laws In Arkansas, Illinois, Kan\nsas, Missouri, Nebraska, South Dakota,\nTennessee and Indiana will be carefully\nconsidered at the conference.\nOFFERINGS.\nAlthough no formal Spring opening\nwill take place, one of the most at\ntractive places to lovers of handsomo I\nfurniture and other household goods\nwill be the big Megary furniture store,\nat Sixth and Tatnall streets. Here may\nbe found everything that Is required i\nto fit out a pretty home, but especially\nattractive at this season Is the store's j\nsplendid stock of summer mattings,\ngrass rugs, cane porch furniture, ham-\nmocks and portiers. One would doubt\nless have to be as finical as Beau\nBrummel to be able to choose at a\nglance from the hundreds of manvi\nspring and summer house furnishings\non view in the store. A\nA first choice of the summer goods\nby the clever housewife would be one\nof the fine handsome big refrigerators,\nthe finest makes of refrigerators being\none of the proudest strictly summer ex\nhibits of the store. Then there are bed- j\nroom suites In maple, walnut and gold\nen oak, which although not strictly\nsummer selections are nevertheless a\nstrong temptation to the shopper. A\nhandsome display of china and glass\nware Is also a delight to the eye. Up\nstairs will be found articles which will\nbe In heavy demand as soon as the\nbalmy weather of porch parties comes,\nportiers, curtains, pillow covers, util\nity boxes, and a full line of hammocks\nOf course. It Is not necessary to men\ntlon the splendid line of go-carts. Al\ntogether the^prlng shopper will have\nlittle trouble finding satisfaction at the\nMegary store and the store anticipates\na busy season.\nMEGARY'S ATTRACTIVE\nBig Store at Sixth and Tatnall Streets\nShows Choice Summer Goods.\nduee alcohol from currants In Greece.\nThe spirit has proved of great use as\nan Illuminant and driving small en\ngines.\nBelt Says\nDON'T SCRAPE YOUR FACE\nSHAVE IT with one of our VELVBT-KUT RAZORS.\nLAR buys one with a full guarantee.\nready Gillette SAFETY RAZORS at *1 and \u00bb5 each respectively.\nLather. Brushes, Shaving Soaps, Creams, etc.\nONE DOL\nA fine Strop for 98c. Ever\nI\n\n(Established 1830.)\nJ Pharmacist, Sixth and Market Strecta\nGERMAN PRESS\nIS PACIFIED\nChancellor Von Buelow Se\ncures an Apology and\nHis Speech Reported\nBy United Press Leased Special Wire.\nBERLIN, March 26\u2014Chancellor\nPrince Von Buelow will address the\nReichstag on Germany's colonial policy\nto-day. The reporters will \"coevr\"\nhis speech and the newspapers wilt\nprint it.\nHerr Groeber has said he was eorr^\nhs called the press repr\u00e9sent\u00e2t!\nswine and everyoody\u2014except\nGroeber\u2014Is satisfied.\nTo Chancellor Von Buelow Is glvev\nthe credit for settling the newspapet\nmen's strike. His colonial speech wat\nall ready, the time wae ripe for hh\ndelivery and he wanted to make 4\nwithout loss of time. He cared a goo<\ndeal more, however, about having th<\ncountry know what he said than hi\ndid for the Reichstag's view,\nSo he brought all kinds of pressvn\nto bear on Centrist Leader Groeber\nto force an apology to the press. Fin*\na\"y he apologized,\nj\n\nfor your spring planting all kinds al\nFruit, Shade. Fancy and Ornamental\nTrees, Shrubbery, and all kinds of nur\nsery stock. Privet hedge a specialty\nfrom the old reliable firm of Hoopet\nBros. Thomas of West Chester. AL\nkinds of planting and pruning attend\ned to.\nSeed Oats\nI\n\n\u2014and\u2014\nSeed Potatoes\nWHITE BROS.\nFront Orange Sts.\nDelmsrvla 2236\nD. A. Phone 1316\nORDER NOW\nTHOMAS A. BETTY, Salesman,\n111 E. Seventh St., Wilmington, Del,\nD. A. Phone 8046D.","height":"21456","width":"15648"}}
